A: You can use the PrintWriter.write in a Servlet like this:

```java
protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) throws ServletException, IOException {
    response.setContentType("text/html");
    PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();
    out.println("<html><body>");
    out.println("<h1>Hello, World!!!</h1>");
    out.println("</body></html>");
}
```

This will write the string "Hello, World!!!" to the HTTP response. The `response.getWriter()` method returns a `PrintWriter` object which is used to write the response to the client.

The `doGet` method is a method in the `HttpServlet` class that is called when a GET request is made to the servlet. The `doGet` method is overridden here to write a simple HTML page to the response.

The `setContentType` method is used to set the content type of the response to "text/html", which tells the client that the response is an HTML document.

The `println` method is used to write the HTML to the response. The HTML includes a heading that says "Hello, World!!!".

